    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>dark post</strong> is a paid social media ad that appears in targeted users' feeds but is not published on the advertiser's public profile or page. On Meta it is called an <strong>unpublished page post</strong>; on LinkedIn it is <strong>Direct Sponsored Content</strong>. Dark posts let marketers test many creative variants at once without cluttering the brand's public timeline.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Format</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Unpublished ad</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Paid Advertising</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Best for</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Creative A/B testing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">If you have ever run 8 headline variants on the same campaign without wanting your public page to look like a spam factory, you have already run dark posts. It is the default format for any serious paid social team.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a dark post?</h2>
        <p>A dark post is an ad that lives entirely inside the ad platform. It is created in Meta Ads Manager, LinkedIn Campaign Manager, or the X ad tool, targeted at a specific audience, and delivered into their feed — but the post itself is never pushed to your brand's public page. Organic followers do not see it in their timeline, and anyone who visits your page will not find it there either.</p>
        <p>The name varies by platform:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Meta (Facebook + Instagram)</strong> — "unpublished page post"</li>
          <li><strong>LinkedIn</strong> — "Direct Sponsored Content"</li>
          <li><strong>X / Twitter</strong> — "promoted-only tweet"</li>
          <li><strong>TikTok</strong> — "Spark Ad" (published) vs "non-Spark Ad" (dark)</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Where the name comes from</div>
          <p>"Dark" refers to visibility on your own page, not to anything hidden from the platform or the user. Users see the ad in their feed and can like, comment, and share it — <strong>the post is fully public to the audience seeing it</strong>. It is only invisible to your organic followers who are not in the target segment.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why dark posts matter for paid social</h2>
        <p>Every high-spend paid social team uses dark posts. Three reasons drive that:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Test velocity.</strong> You can run 5 to 20 creative variants per ad set without your public page filling up with "which of these do you like better?" spam. Faster testing means faster learning.</li>
          <li><strong>Audience-specific messaging.</strong> Different audiences see different copy, offers, and hooks. A CTO sees ROI language; a founder sees speed-to-hire language. Neither one sees the other's ad.</li>
          <li><strong>Brand feed control.</strong> Your public page stays a curated brand channel — announcements, wins, culture — while all the messy testing happens in the ad account.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How dark posts actually work</h2>
        <p>The workflow is the same across every ad platform:</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># 1. Create the ad inside Ads Manager (not on your page)</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Creative:</span> <span class="uf-new">headline_v3 + image_v7 + CTA "Get demo"</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># 2. Target a specific audience</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Audience:</span> <span class="uf-new">SaaS founders · US · 25-45 · LinkedIn lookalike 1%</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># 3. Ad delivers to feed — but never to your page</span><br>
          <span class="uf-old">brand.com/page</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-comment">nothing new posted</span><br>
          <span class="uf-new">audience.feed</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-status">ad delivered</span>
        </div>

        <h3>How to build one on Meta</h3>
        <p>Inside Meta Ads Manager, at the ad level, choose <strong>Create Ad</strong> instead of <strong>Use Existing Post</strong>. Attach the connected page, upload creative, write copy — and skip the "publish to page" step. The resulting post has a unique ID that can be reused across multiple ad sets.</p>

        <h3>How to build one on LinkedIn</h3>
        <p>In LinkedIn Campaign Manager, open the connected company page and choose <strong>Create Content</strong> then <strong>Direct Sponsored Content</strong>. LinkedIn stores the post at the page level but marks it as unpublished — it does not appear in the page's feed.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Dark post vs boosted post vs organic post</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>Lives on page?</th><th>Paid?</th><th>Best for</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Dark post</strong></td>
                <td>No — invisible to page</td>
                <td>Yes</td>
                <td>Multi-variant testing, audience-specific creative</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Boosted post</strong></td><td>Yes — starts organic</td><td>Yes (added later)</td><td>Quick reach amplification for a proven post</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Organic post</strong></td><td>Yes</td><td>No</td><td>Brand voice, community, algorithm signals</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Whitelisted creator ad</strong></td><td>On creator's page</td><td>Yes</td><td>Running ads through an influencer's handle</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real dark post examples</h2>
        <p>Two patterns cover 80% of how teams use them.</p>

        <h3>1. Multi-headline test at scale</h3>
        <p>A B2B SaaS team ran 8 headline variants on the same image, targeted at 4 job titles on LinkedIn (CTO, VP Eng, Head of Product, Founder). That is 32 dark posts total. After 5 days the "CTO + outcome-focused headline" combo showed a <strong>3x higher CTR</strong> than the average. The team killed 28 variants and scaled the winner.</p>

        <h3>2. Offer test by neighborhood</h3>
        <p>A local fitness studio ran two offer variants on Instagram — "50% off first month" vs "free trial class" — targeted at 6 different neighborhoods within 5 miles. The 50% offer beat the free trial by <strong>40% on cost-per-lead</strong> in every neighborhood. Neither offer ever appeared on the studio's public feed.</p>

        <h3>3. Retargeting with different creative per stage</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Cold audience — awareness message</span><br>
          <span class="uf-old">audience: no site visit</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">"Meet Stacc — SEO on autopilot"</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Warm audience — case study proof</span><br>
          <span class="uf-old">audience: pricing page visit</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">"How Fairview grew 3x in 90 days"</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Hot audience — direct offer</span><br>
          <span class="uf-old">audience: demo page abandoners</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">"Book a demo, get $500 credit"</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Dark post vs boosted post — which to use</h2>
        <p>Both are paid. The difference is whether the post exists on your page.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use a dark post when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You are testing multiple creative variants</li>
              <li>Different audiences need different messaging</li>
              <li>You do not want ad copy on your public feed</li>
              <li>You are running retargeting sequences</li>
              <li>You want reusable post IDs across ad sets</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use a boosted post when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>An organic post is already performing well</li>
              <li>You want social proof (likes, comments) to compound</li>
              <li>You need a quick reach lift with minimal setup</li>
              <li>The audience is broad, not segmented</li>
              <li>The post is core brand content worth showing everyone</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for dark posts</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Test one variable at a time.</strong> Change headline OR image OR CTA — not all three. Otherwise you cannot attribute the win.</li>
          <li><strong>Run 3 to 5 variants per ad set.</strong> More than 5 spreads budget too thin for the platform to find a winner.</li>
          <li><strong>Give each variant 3 to 5 days.</strong> Kill the bottom 40% after that window and reallocate budget to the top 20%.</li>
          <li><strong>Reuse winning post IDs.</strong> A single winning dark post can be dropped into 10 new ad sets. Social proof (likes, comments) compounds across placements.</li>
          <li><strong>Match creative to audience temperature.</strong> Cold audiences need hooks; warm audiences need proof; hot audiences need offers.</li>
          <li><strong>Track by post ID, not campaign name.</strong> A single winning creative can outlive 5 campaign iterations.</li>
          <li><strong>Preview on desktop and mobile.</strong> A hook that works on mobile Instagram can die on desktop Facebook. Check both before spending.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — forgetting to check comments</div>
          <p>Dark posts collect likes and comments just like any post — but you cannot see them on your page. Set up a comment monitoring workflow (Meta's Inbox, Sprout, or a Slack alert) so you do not leave <strong>angry customers or fresh leads sitting in dark-post comment threads for weeks</strong>.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common dark post mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Ignoring comment moderation</strong> — comments still happen, and negative ones can tank your relevance score if unanswered.</li>
          <li><strong>Testing too many variables at once</strong> — makes results unattributable and wastes budget.</li>
          <li><strong>Killing variants too early</strong> — under 3 days is usually noise, not signal.</li>
          <li><strong>Not reusing winning post IDs</strong> — losing all the social proof stacked on the winning creative.</li>
          <li><strong>Broad targeting with dark posts</strong> — if the audience is huge, a boosted post plus algorithm optimization is cheaper.</li>
          <li><strong>Forgetting UTM tags</strong> — dark posts do not carry organic post metadata. Tag every link.</li>
        </ul>

